1
00:00:00,450 --> 00:00:11,000
Here is the whole machine. We collect public data,
organize it in a lakehouse, transform it into clues,
run model engines, and keep only evidence that passes
checks.

2
00:00:12,450 --> 00:00:22,450
First, raw data lands safely. Beach lab samples,
weather, sensors, water quality, and research feeds
arrive before we change names, units, or dates.

3
00:00:24,450 --> 00:00:35,125
The lakehouse has three shelves. Bronze keeps the
original files. Silver holds cleaned tables. Gold
stores model runs, predictions, metrics, and
leaderboards.

4
00:00:37,450 --> 00:00:47,925
Transforms are the cleanup team. They fix units, match
stations, join sources by time and place, build
features, and block future answers from leaking into
training.

5
00:00:50,450 --> 00:01:01,750
The folders act like rooms in a school lab. Source-
shaped datasets, silver tables, gold results, research
engines, reports, and the Mission Control site each
have a clear home.

6
00:01:03,450 --> 00:01:14,175
Feature builders turn tables into useful clues: recent
history, rain and runoff, physics pi groups, tensor
factors, and oxygen covariates for stress screening.

7
00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:27,475
Then the engines compete. Simple logistic models, tree
boosters, neural nets, tensor factorization, and zero-
shot readouts all get graded on the same target
question.

8
00:01:29,450 --> 00:01:41,000
Each target engine asks one exact question. Beach
bacteria, surprise-onset events, oxygen stress,
harmful algae signals, and state QA each use its own
grading rule.

9
00:01:42,450 --> 00:01:53,325
A result is not trusted just because it looks good.
Holdout tests, baselines, confidence intervals, null
checks, calibration, and critic reviews decide what
survives.

10
00:01:55,450 --> 00:02:05,675
Right now, several findings survive. The strongest
story is not one magic model. It is a set of checked
claims, with some ideas held and weaker stories
dropped.

11
00:02:08,450 --> 00:02:18,625
Mission Control is the human layer. It turns those
files into dashboards, claim cards, reports, and
videos so people can see what happened and why it
matters.
